  const aiSafetyId = uuidv4();

  createNode(nodes, aiId, rootId, "AI Features", "IDMPro includes powerful AI capabilities to help you generate content, create images, and build outlines faster. AI features are accessed through the violet sparkles icon and the image button in the toolbar.", []);

  // AI Plans
  createNode(nodes, aiPlansId, aiId, "AI Plans (FREE vs PREMIUM)", "IDMPro offers two AI plans:\n\nFREE Plan:\n- AI content generation\n- External source ingestion\n- Standard AI processing\n\nPREMIUM Plan ($9.99/month):\n- All FREE features\n- AI image generation\n- Advanced AI model\n- Suboutline summaries\n- Teach mode\n- Consistency checks\n- Priority processing\n- RAG-powered knowledge base (coming soon): Semantic search across all your outlines using vector embeddings for faster, more accurate cross-outline queries\n\nTo manage your plan: Click the AI menu (sparkles icon) > 'Manage AI Plan...'");

  // AI Menu
  createNode(nodes, aiMenuId, aiId, "Smart Tools menu", "Access intelligent features from a single menu:\n\n1. Click the sparkles icon in the toolbar — this is the Smart Tools menu (renamed 2026-06-04; previously \"AI Features\")\n2. The menu shows:\n   - Quick Command — type or speak any natural-language request (also ⌘K). It doesn't just search — it can act on your outline. For example, say 'add a node called Budget' to create a new node right there, or 'create an outline called Trip Plan' to spin up a whole new outline.\n   - Reformat with AI… — restructure a node's content (or a selection) per a plain-language instruction (\"turn into a bulleted list\", \"make each line a heading\")\n   - Transform outline with AI… — restructure a whole suboutline by describing what should change\n   - Generate Suboutline from Topic — builds out a structured suboutline under the selected node\n   - Capture from image — extract a hierarchical outline from a whiteboard photo, mind map, sticky-note board, or slide screenshot (added 2026-06-11)\n   - Translate this section — translate a suboutline into another language\n   - Ask Your Outlines — search your outlines with natural language (previously \"Knowledge Chat\")\n\nResearch & Import has its own home in the toolbar's Import menu (BookDown icon), not the Smart Tools menu, so source-merging lives next to the other import actions. The Import menu also hosts \"Link to Outline…\" for inserting a cross-outline link node, and \"Refresh from Web\" (moved here 2026-06-06 — it brings external web content INTO existing nodes, so it fits the Import metaphor).\n\nYour current plan (Free or Premium) is shown in the menu header.");

  // Multimedia AI — Capture from image + Share as YouTube package (2026-06-11)
  const aiCaptureFromImageId = "ai-capture-from-image";
  createNode(nodes, aiCaptureFromImageId, aiId, "Capture from image", "Turn any image into a structured outline. Useful for whiteboard photos, hand-drawn mind maps, sticky-note brainstorms, and screenshots of slides or textbook pages.\n\n**How to open it:**\n• Smart Tools menu (sparkles icon) > 'Capture from image'\n• On iOS / Android: the dialog also offers a 'Take photo' button that opens the device camera\n\n**The workflow (with preview-and-approve like every other AI transform):**\n1. Pick an image (file picker on desktop, camera on mobile) or drop one onto a node\n2. Optionally add a short context hint to help the AI (e.g. 'brainstorm whiteboard for product launch')\n3. Click 'Extract outline' — the AI returns a proposed hierarchical structure\n4. Review the proposed nodes in the three-panel preview: source thumbnail on the left, proposed outline (editable inline) in the middle, where it lands on the right\n5. Rename or remove individual nodes you don't want\n6. Click 'Add N nodes' — the new structure appends as children of your selected node\n\n**Data protection (the three layers):**\n• An auto-snapshot of your current outline is written to disk before the new nodes are added — recoverable from Restore from Backup at any time\n• Cmd+Z undoes the entire capture as a single step\n• You can pick 'Save as new outline' instead of in-place add — the original stays untouched and the captured structure becomes a derivative\n\n**Provenance:** The source image is stored alongside the outline (a `sourceImageId` is recorded in each new node's metadata). You can always see what generated the content. Storage of the actual image bytes is local-only in v1.\n\n**Usage:** One image capture = ONE generation against your monthly cap, regardless of how many nodes the AI extracts. Bring your own API key in Settings for unlimited use.");

  const ytPackageId = "ai-youtube-package";
  createNode(nodes, ytPackageId, aiId, "Share as YouTube package", "Turn a chapter (a selected node + its descendants) into a complete YouTube content package. Useful when an outline suboutline is the seed for a video and you want everything you need to produce it in one click.\n\n**How to open it:**\n• Toolbar > Export menu (BookUp icon) > 'Share as YouTube package'\n• Right-click the chapter node and pick the same item\n\n**The dialog:**\n1. Pick a target duration — 60 sec, 90 sec, 2 min, or 5 min\n2. Pick a style — Tutorial, Explainer, Promo, or Story\n3. Optionally add an audience hint (e.g. 'developers', 'researchers', 'general')\n4. Click 'Generate'. The AI produces eight outputs at once:\n   - Voiceover script with [shot N] markers and timing cues\n   - Chapter list (YouTube description chapter markers)\n   - 200-300 word YouTube description\n   - Five title variants optimized for CTR\n   - 15-20 SEO tags\n   - Thumbnail composition concept\n   - B-roll prompts ready to paste into Runway / MagicLight / Sora\n   - Screen-recording shot list for the in-app demo segments\n5. Each output is shown in its own tab — review and edit any of them inline\n6. Click 'Export as markdown' for a single .md file, or 'Save as new outline' to keep the package as a derivative outline (one node per output)\n\n**Usage:** One YouTube package = ONE generation against your monthly cap. Bring your own API key in Settings for unlimited use.");

  // Generate Outline from Topic
  createNode(nodes, aiGenerateOutlineId, aiId, "Generate Suboutline from Topic", "Create a structured suboutline from any topic under the selected node:\n\n1. Select a node in your outline\n2. Click AI menu > 'Generate Suboutline from Topic'\n3. The topic field is pre-filled with the selected node's name — edit it if you want\n4. Choose depth, tone, and level settings\n5. Click 'Generate'\n6. AI creates a structured suboutline as children of the selected node\n\nThis is great for building out sections of an existing outline. For example, select a node called 'Market Analysis', generate a suboutline, and you'll get sub-sections like 'Competitor Landscape', 'Target Demographics', etc.");

  // Generate Content for Node
  createNode(nodes, aiGenerateContentId, aiId, "Generate Content for Node", "AI can write detailed content for any node in your outline.\n\nThe AI analyzes your node's title and its position in the hierarchy to generate relevant, contextual content. You control whether to replace existing content, append to it, or cancel.\n\nThe generation considers your outline structure from root to the selected node, ensuring thematic consistency.", []);
  createNode(nodes, aiGenerateHowId, aiGenerateContentId, "How to Trigger", "1. Select any node (except root)\n2. Click the violet sparkles button in the content pane header\n3. AI generates content based on the node's title and context");
  createNode(nodes, aiGenerateContextId, aiGenerateContentId, "Context & Input", "The AI uses:\n- The node's name/title\n- The path of ancestor nodes (for context)\n- Any existing content (as a draft to consider)\n\nThis helps AI generate relevant, contextual content that fits your outline structure.");
  createNode(nodes, aiGenerateConflictId, aiGenerateContentId, "Replace vs Append", "If the node already has content, you'll see options:\n\n- Replace: Overwrite existing content with AI content\n- Append Below: Add AI content after existing content\n- Cancel: Keep existing content unchanged\n\nYour content is never changed without your explicit choice.");

  // Research & Import (formerly Ingest External Source)
  createNode(nodes, aiIngestId, aiId, "Research & Import", "The Research & Import feature is the heart of IDMPro's power. Import content from multiple sources simultaneously, and AI will synthesize them into a unified, structured outline.\n\n**Key Capabilities:**\n• Multi-source synthesis - Import multiple sources at once, AI finds connections\n• Smart defaults - YouTube titles, AI-generated names, automatic introductions\n• Merge or create new - Default merges into current outline, or create fresh\n• Speaker diarization - Audio recordings identify different speakers\n\n**Access:** Toolbar Import menu (BookDown icon) > 'Research & Import'. (Previously lived under the AI menu; moved 2026-06-04 so all import surfaces sit together.)", []);
  createNode(nodes, aiIngestSourcesId, aiIngestId, "Supported Sources", "**YouTube Videos**\n• Paste any YouTube URL\n• Transcript extracted automatically\n• Video title becomes default outline name\n\n**Conversation/Audio**\n• Paste transcript directly\n• Upload audio file for transcription\n• Record live with microphone\n• Speaker diarization identifies who said what\n\n**Documents**\n• PDF files (URL or upload)\n• Word, Excel, PowerPoint\n• Images with OCR text extraction\n\n**Other**\n• Web pages (URL)\n• Plain text/notes\n• Existing outline files (.idm)\n• Video files (audio extracted)");
  createNode(nodes, aiIngestPreviewId, aiIngestId, "Smart Naming & Summaries", "**Automatic Outline Naming:**\n• YouTube videos → Uses video title\n• Other sources → AI generates concise title from content\n• Fallback → Date-based name\n\n**Root Node Introduction:**\nWhen creating a new outline (not merging), the root node automatically gets an AI-generated introduction that summarizes all the content below it. This helps readers quickly understand the context.\n\n**Chapter Introductions:**\nParent/chapter nodes include introductory content that previews their children - no empty headers.");
  createNode(nodes, aiIngestMergeId, aiIngestId, "Merge vs New Outline", "**Default: Merge into Current Outline**\n• New content is synthesized with your existing outline\n• AI finds connections between old and new material\n• Preserves your existing structure\n• Content from both existing and new sources is integrated under shared themes\n\n**Option: Create New Outline**\n• Check 'Create new outline instead'\n• Provide a name or let AI generate one\n• Your current outline is unchanged\n\nThe merge behavior ensures you can continuously build knowledge on a topic from multiple sources over time.\n\n**Node Formatting:**\nResearch outlines use short names (2-6 words) as tree labels with detailed content in the content pane. Even in comprehensive mode, node names stay concise while all prose and detail goes into the content field.");

  // Pending Import Recovery
  const pendingImportId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, pendingImportId, aiIngestId, "Pending Import Recovery", "On the desktop (Electron) app, if a Research & Import operation times out or the app closes during an import, the result is saved automatically.\n\nOn next launch:\n1. A recovery dialog appears\n2. It shows the pending import that was interrupted\n3. You can choose to apply the import or discard it\n\nThis ensures you never lose a long-running import due to network issues or accidental app closure.");

  // Undo Merge
  const undoMergeId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, undoMergeId, aiIngestId, "Unmerge", "When merging research into an existing outline, a snapshot of your outline is taken before the merge begins.\n\nIf the merge produces bad results, look for the **Unmerge button** in the toolbar — it appears right after the Research & Import button as an orange circular arrow icon. Clicking it restores your outline to its exact pre-merge state.\n\nThe Unmerge button persists until you click it or perform another merge (which creates a new backup). You can freely edit the outline and still unmerge later. The backup survives app restarts. Only the most recent merge can be unmerged.");

  // AI Image Generation
  createNode(nodes, aiImageGenId, aiId, "AI Image Generation (Premium)", "Create custom illustrations with AI:\n\n1. Click the violet Image button in the content toolbar\n2. Describe the image you want (be specific about style, colors, composition)\n3. Choose an aspect ratio (square, landscape, portrait)\n4. Click 'Generate Image'\n\nThe AI-generated image is inserted directly into your content.\n\n**Tips for better results:**\n• Be specific: 'A serene mountain lake at sunset with purple sky' vs 'a lake'\n• Mention style: 'digital art', 'watercolor', 'photorealistic', 'minimalist'\n• Include composition details: 'close-up', 'wide angle', 'from above'\n\n**Plan & cost:** AI image generation, the premium podcast voice, and audio transcription are paid-per-use premium features. For now they run ONLY on your own API key — add a Gemini key (images), OpenAI key (premium podcast voice), or AssemblyAI key (transcription) in Settings → AI Service Keys. A small free 'taste' of these features (a limited lifetime number, counted per account on our servers so it can't be reset) turns on automatically once SecondBrainWare has its own funded billing account; until then, non-key users are shown an upgrade prompt instead of a paid call, so a paid call is never made by accident. **Mind Map and Flowchart visuals are always free** — they're drawn locally from your outline structure with no AI and don't count against anything. The free podcast/video voice option (your Mac's built-in narrator) also stays free and unlimited.");

  // Generate Podcast
  createNode(nodes, aiPodcastId, aiId, "Generate Podcast", "Convert any suboutline into a conversational audio podcast.\n\nHow to use:\n1. Right-click any node in the outline\n2. Select 'Generate Podcast'\n3. Configure your podcast:\n   • **Style**: Two-Host Discussion, Single Narrator, Interview, or Debate\n   • **Voices**: Choose from 6 OpenAI voices for each speaker\n   • **Length**: Brief (2-3 min), Standard (5-8 min), or Detailed (10-15 min)\n   • **Quality**: Standard (faster) or HD (higher quality)\n4. Click 'Generate' and wait for the AI to write the script and synthesize audio\n5. Preview the audio in the built-in player\n6. Click 'Save Audio File' to save the MP3\n\nThe script viewer lets you read along with the generated dialogue. You can also discard and regenerate with different settings.\n\nYour podcast preferences (style, voices, length, and audio quality) are remembered across sessions, so you don't need to reconfigure each time. When switching to a new style for the first time, your preferred voices carry over automatically.\n\n**Voices — always audible, never silent (mirrors the Video feature):** On the desktop app your podcast ALWAYS records. If you've added an OpenAI key in Settings you get natural AI voices, and they run on YOUR key (BYOK) — not ours. If you haven't added a key, the podcast still records using your Mac's built-in voices (free, offline, no key needed), giving each speaker a distinct voice so the back-and-forth still sounds like two people. The app automatically picks the best-quality Apple voices installed on your Mac — if you've downloaded any of the higher-quality 'Enhanced' or 'Premium' system voices (a free one-time download in System Settings > Accessibility > Spoken Content), it uses those for noticeably more natural narration; otherwise it uses the standard ones. It's the SAME OpenAI key the Generate Video feature uses, so if you already added it for video you don't re-enter it here.\n\n**On iPhone and iPad, free too:** keyless users get an audible, two-voice podcast synthesized right on the device using Apple's built-in voices — no key, no cost, nothing sent to a paid service. If you've added your own OpenAI key it uses that for premium AI voices instead. On the web, podcast audio uses your own key if you've added one, otherwise our cloud text-to-speech.");

  // Generate Video
  const aiVideoId = "ai-generate-video";
  createNode(nodes, aiVideoId, aiId, "Generate Video (Pro)", "Turn a chapter — a selected node and its sub-points — into a narrated slideshow video, complete with your own branding. Great for turning a section of your outline into something you can post to YouTube, share in a class, or drop into a presentation.\n\n**Where it lives:** Desktop app only. Open the Export menu (BookUp icon) and choose 'Generate Video'. On the web and iOS the dialog is honest that rendering runs on the Mac desktop app — because the video is built right on your machine, nothing is uploaded to a server.\n\n**What you can customize (the Style section):**\n• **Logo** — upload your own logo (PNG, JPEG, SVG, or WebP); it appears on every slide\n• **Accent color** — pick a preset or a custom color that tints the slides\n• **Theme** — dark or light slide background\n• **Slide visuals** — combinable, independent options (tick any mix you like): **Mind maps** (a mind map of each section, drawn automatically from that part of your outline), **Photos** (a free public-domain photo matched to your slides), and **Video clips** (a MOVING free public-domain clip behind your detail slides, with a dark scrim keeping the text readable). They mix per slide — sections favor a mind map, detail slides favor a video clip if you turned clips on, otherwise a photo; leave everything unchecked for clean text-only slides. The default is **Mind maps + Photos** (reliable and free); Video clips is off by default because clip relevance can't be guaranteed — when it's on and no strong match is found, that slide quietly uses a photo instead. Photos and clips come only from free, license-clean public-domain sources — photos from Openverse (CC0 / Public Domain); clips from Wikimedia Commons (public domain / CC0, no key needed), or from Pexels or Pixabay if you've added one of their free keys — so everything costs nothing and is safe to use commercially. A small 'media-credits' text file listing each photo and clip's source is saved next to your video. Everything fails safe: if a visual can't be fetched (say you're offline) that slide quietly falls back to a photo, then to text, so a missing visual never breaks the video or costs a penny\n• **Narrator voice** — choose from the same set of natural AI voices as the Podcast feature\n• **Detail** — how deep into the outline the video goes: **Overview** (top sections only), **Standard** (sections and subsections), **Deep** (three levels), or **Full outline** (every level, at any depth). Standard is the default; pick Full outline to turn an entire outline into one video. Your choice is remembered for next time.\n\nThere's a live preview of a slide so you can see your look before rendering. A large-chapter warning appears for long sections so you can decide before kicking off a multi-minute render.\n\n**How it works, briefly:** each point in the chapter — down to the Detail level you chose — becomes a slide; an AI voiceover narrates the slides; the slides and audio are stitched into a finished MP4, saved to your Documents · IDMPro Videos folder. While it renders, a live progress bar shows exactly where it's up to (for example 'Rendering slide 3 of 12' or 'Stitching video') along with an estimated time remaining that updates as it goes. When it's done you can open the video with one click.\n\n**Voiceover:** Your video ALWAYS narrates — it is never silent. If you've added an OpenAI key in Settings you get natural AI text-to-speech; if you haven't, the video still narrates using your Mac's built-in voice (free, offline, no key needed).\n\n**Plan:** Everyone gets **10 free videos** to try it out (those free videos carry a small 'Made with IDMPro' mark). Upgrade to **Pro** for unlimited videos with no watermark.");

  // Create Content for Descendants
  const aiDescendantsId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiDescendantsId, aiId, "Create Content for Descendants", "Generate AI content for all child nodes of a parent at once.\n\nHow to use:\n1. Right-click a parent node (one that has children)\n2. Select 'Create Content for Descendants'\n3. AI generates content for every child node based on its title and context\n\nThis is a fast way to flesh out an entire section of your outline. Each child node receives content tailored to its title and position in the hierarchy. Existing content in child nodes is preserved - only empty nodes get new content.");

  createNode(nodes, aiLiveBooksId, aiId, "Refresh from Web", "Refresh from Web keeps your documents from going stale. It takes a node and everything under it, asks AI to refresh the content against the latest information on the internet, and shows you exactly what would change before anything is touched. (Internal code name: LIVE BOOKS — that name still appears in some technical files but not in the UI.)\n\nHow to use:\n1. Select the node you want to refresh (select the top/root node to refresh the whole outline)\n2. Open it one of three ways:\n   • Toolbar: Import menu (BookDown icon) > 'Refresh from Web' (moved here 2026-06-06 — it brings external web content INTO existing nodes, so it fits the Import metaphor)\n   • Command Palette (Cmd/Ctrl+K) > 'Refresh from Web'\n   • Keyboard: Cmd+Shift+R (Mac) / Ctrl+Shift+R (Windows/Linux)\n3. Choose how to update:\n   • Merge & augment (recommended) — keeps content that's still accurate, fixes what's outdated, folds in new developments\n   • Overwrite / regenerate — rewrites each section from scratch\n4. By default you get a side-by-side preview of every proposed change. Accept or reject each node individually, then click Apply. Nothing changes until you approve.\n5. (Optional) Tick 'Apply automatically without previewing' before running if you want changes applied directly — this is off by default and must be turned on deliberately each time.\n\nWhat it protects:\n• Nodes you edited by hand are automatically skipped so the refresh never clobbers your own writing. Skipped nodes are listed in the preview with an 'Include anyway' button if you want them refreshed too.\n\nSources & attribution:\n• Every refreshed node carries its sources. A small 'Sources' chip appears on the node — click it to see the citations and which AI model produced the refresh (e.g. 'Refreshed with Gemini 3.5 Flash'). Citations travel with the outline through save and export.\n• With cloud AI, refreshes use live web search and list the real pages used. With local AI (no internet), the refresh uses the model's built-in knowledge and clearly states that no web sources were available — it never invents citations.\n\nRefresh from Web is personal and local: it only changes your own copy of the outline after you approve.");

  // Translate (#52) — built on the same transform engine as LIVE BOOKS.
  const aiTranslateId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiTranslateId, aiId, "Translate this section", "Translate any node and its descendants into another language, with the same preview-and-approve safety as Refresh from Web.\n\nBuilt for globally distributed teams (Boston ↔ Shanghai ↔ São Paulo): the language list is ordered so the most-requested global collaboration languages — Chinese (Simplified), Portuguese (Brazilian), Spanish, French, Japanese, Korean, German, Italian, Hindi — appear at the top.\n\nHow to use:\n1. Select the node you want to translate (select the top/root to translate the whole outline)\n2. Open it one of two ways:\n   • Toolbar: Smart Tools menu (sparkles icon) > 'Translate this section'\n   • Command Palette (Cmd/Ctrl+K) > 'Translate this section'\n3. Pick a target language from the dropdown (no default — you have to choose). Optionally tick 'Use local AI' to keep the translation entirely on your machine via Ollama.\n4. Click 'Translate & preview'. Each node's translation is shown side-by-side with the original. Reject any you don't want, then click 'Apply N translations'.\n\nFormatting (headings, lists, bold, links) is preserved. Proper nouns and code stay as-is. Nodes you edited by hand are auto-skipped with a per-node 'Include anyway' override, so translation never clobbers your edits.\n\nUsage: One Translate (regardless of how many nodes are in the suboutline) counts as ONE generation against your monthly cap. Bring your own API key in Settings for unlimited use.");

  // Reformat with AI — single-shot per-node content reformat driven by a
  // plain-language instruction.
  const aiReformatId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiReformatId, aiId, "Reformat with AI", "Reformat the content in a node by describing the format you want in plain English. Same workflow you'd use with an AI assistant for cleanup — built into the app.\n\nHow to open it:\n• Smart Tools menu (sparkles icon) > 'Reformat with AI…' — reformats the whole node\n• Right-click anywhere in the content area > 'Reformat with AI…' — reformats the whole node, or just your selection if text is selected\n• Select some text in the content editor — the floating formatting toolbar (bubble menu) shows a violet wand button at the LEFT END with a small 'Most Powerful' badge; click it to reformat just the selection (moved to first position 2026-06-05 to make it the eye-magnet of the toolbar)\n• Command Palette (Cmd/Ctrl+K) > 'Reformat with AI…'\n\nThe dialog:\n1. Type the format you want — e.g. 'turn into a bulleted list', 'make each line a heading', 'convert to a markdown table', 'tighten spacing and remove empty lines'.\n2. Or click one of the example chips below the input to fill it in.\n3. Click 'Preview reformat'. The AI returns a reformatted version, shown side-by-side with the original.\n4. Click 'Apply' to keep it, 'Modify instruction' to tweak and try again, or 'Cancel' to discard.\n\nWhat it preserves: Your actual words and meaning. Reformat changes structure and presentation — it doesn't invent new content or delete substance unless you explicitly ask it to summarise.\n\nOptional: Tick 'Use local AI (Ollama)' to run the reformat entirely on-device.\n\nUsage: One reformat = ONE generation against your monthly cap, regardless of how long the content is. Available on every tier (Free trial, Student, Pro) and free with your own API key.");

  // Transform outline with AI — whole-suboutline structural transformation
  // driven by a plain-language instruction. Distinct from Reformat with AI,
  // which operates on a single node's content body.
  const aiTransformOutlineId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiTransformOutlineId, aiId, "Transform outline with AI", "Restructure a whole suboutline (or the whole outline) by describing what should change in plain English. Where 'Reformat with AI' rewrites the contents of ONE node, 'Transform outline with AI' changes the SHAPE of the outline itself — adding, removing, renaming, merging, splitting, or moving nodes.\n\nHow to open it:\n• Smart Tools menu (sparkles icon) > 'Transform outline with AI…'\n• Command Palette (Cmd/Ctrl+K) > 'Transform outline with AI'\n\nScope rule:\n• If you have a node selected, the transform operates on that node and everything beneath it.\n• If nothing is selected, it operates on the WHOLE current outline (root down).\n\nThe dialog:\n1. Type how you want to transform the suboutline — e.g. 'reorganize alphabetically by name', 'merge chapters with fewer than three children into a Misc chapter', 'promote leaf nodes about [topic] to top-level chapters'.\n2. Or click one of the example chips below the input to fill it in.\n3. Click 'Preview transform'. The AI returns a transformed version and the dialog shows a Before / After tree view with color coding: green = added, red strike-through = removed, amber = renamed, blue = moved.\n4. A one-line summary at the top tells you exactly how many nodes will be added, removed, renamed, or moved.\n5. Click 'Apply' to commit the change, 'Modify instruction' to tweak and try again, or 'Cancel' to discard.\n\nLarge-suboutline safeguard: If the suboutline is bigger than ~2,000 nodes, the dialog surfaces a friendly warning. You can still proceed, but selecting a smaller scope first usually gives a better result.\n\nWhat it preserves: Node IDs for anything kept, the parentId anchor on the suboutline's root (so the suboutline stays in its place inside the larger outline), and node TYPE unless you explicitly ask to change it. Newly created nodes get fresh IDs.\n\nOptional: Tick 'Use local AI (Ollama)' to run the transform entirely on-device.\n\nUsage: One transform = ONE generation against your monthly cap, regardless of how many nodes change. Available on every tier (Free trial, Student, Pro) and free with your own API key.");

  // Derivative outlines — save AI-transform results as a NEW outline instead
  // of overwriting the original. Third protective layer in IDMPro's
  // data-protection model (Undo > Auto-snapshot > Derivative-by-default).
  const aiDerivativeId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiDerivativeId, aiId, "Derivative outlines", "When the AI rewrites an outline for you — Transform Outline, Reformat, Refresh from Web — the safer default is to save the result as a NEW outline. Your original stays exactly as it was. The new outline is a 'derivative': it remembers which outline it came from, and shows up nested under the original in the sidebar with a small fork badge.\n\n**Why we default to this:**\nAn outline can represent years of your work. A bad AI rewrite is fast to apply and slow to recover from. By creating a new outline instead, you keep the original untouched and get the option to compare, switch, or delete the derivative without any loss.\n\n**How it shows up in the transform dialog:**\nEvery transform dialog (Transform Outline with AI, Reformat with AI, Refresh from Web, Translate) shows a 'What should we do with the result?' radio with two choices:\n\n• **Save as new outline (recommended)** — default for Transform / Reformat / Refresh. A new outline is created with the result; your original is not modified. The new outline's name is auto-suggested from your prompt ('Middle School Version', 'Academic Rigorous Version', etc.) and you can edit the label before applying.\n• **Replace this outline** — second option. Writes the result over your current outline. The auto-snapshot still fires before the change, and Cmd+Z still undoes it — so even this path is recoverable.\n\nTranslate is the one transform whose default is 'Replace this outline' — translating preserves content per language and you've already chosen the target language, so replacement is the expected behavior. Derivative is still available as an opt-in.\n\n**Where derivatives live in the sidebar:**\nDerivatives appear nested under their parent outline, similar to cross-outline links — same chevron, same indent. The icon is a small fork badge (purple) instead of the regular outline icon, and hovering it shows the derivation label.\n\n**The 'Derived from' banner:**\nWhen you open a derivative outline, a small chip near the top reads 'Derived from [Parent name]' with an 'Open original' button to switch back. The chip is unobtrusive — it doesn't dominate the layout — but it makes the lineage obvious at a glance.\n\n**Multi-level derivation:**\nYou can derive from a derivative. A derivative-of-a-derivative renders as a grandchild in the sidebar. The chain is preserved.\n\n**If you delete the parent:**\nDerivatives orphan gracefully. They still exist (you don't lose them), they just no longer nest under anything — they appear at top-level with a muted '(orphan derivative)' hint.\n\n**This is the third layer of outline data protection.**\nLayer 1: Cmd+Z undoes every transform. Layer 2: an auto-snapshot is written to disk before any in-place transform. Layer 3: derivative-by-default means the in-place transform isn't even the default — your original is preserved without any action from you.");

  // Discovery Hints — sticky "Did You Know?" tips that surface the first
  // time a new user hits a feature worth knowing about.
  const discoveryHintsId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, discoveryHintsId, aiId, "Did You Know? tips", "IDMPro surfaces sticky discovery cards in the lower-right corner the first time you reach a feature worth knowing about — short, conversational, one-tip-at-a-time.\n\n**Examples (v1):**\n• First text selection in the editor → 'Reformat with AI is here' tip (points at the violet wand at the left end of the bubble menu)\n• Six seconds later → 'Smart Tools = your AI toolkit' tip (points at the sparkle icon in the toolbar)\n• First time you create an outline → 'Link one outline to another' tip, then 10 seconds later an 'Import and Export live in the toolbar' tip\n• First time you open a BYOK key entry in Settings → 'Bring your own API key for unlimited use' tip\n• Once your outline has a few nodes of real content → a one-time 'Ready to turn this into something?' nudge pointing at Export (video, podcast, website)\n\n**Brand-new users** also see a single, skippable 'What you can make here' welcome panel the first time they open the app — a quick showcase of the app's outputs (Video, Podcast, Website, Docs/Export) and inputs (Import, AI + Second Brain). It shows once, has a 'Get started' / 'Skip' button, never reappears after you dismiss it, and is fully suppressed in Professional mode. The Import and Export toolbar icons also carry value tooltips that say what they do — Import brings in YouTube/PDFs/web/notes; Export turns your outline into a video, podcast, website, or 20+ formats.\n\n**How they behave:**\n• Tips do NOT auto-dismiss — click the 'Got it' button when you've read it\n• Multiple tips stagger so they never pile up\n• Each tip has the eyebrow 'Did You Know?' and a violet sparkle so they're distinguishable from regular toasts\n\n**Two ways to dismiss (2026-06-05):**\nEvery 'Did You Know?' card has TWO controls along its bottom edge: a checkbox labelled 'Don't show me this again', and the 'Got it' button.\n• **Just click 'Got it'** (checkbox UNCHECKED): the card disappears for now, but the same tip is eligible to pop up again the next time the same thing happens (e.g. the next time you select text). Useful when you want the card out of the way but a refresher later would be welcome.\n• **Check the box, then click 'Got it'**: the tip goes onto a permanent 'never show again' list and won't appear for you ever again — not even if you later switch Professional mode off.\n\n**Professional mode (turn off all tips):**\nSettings → Tips → 'Professional mode' is the master switch. Turn it ON to suppress every tip — anything currently visible disappears and no new tips will fire. Turn it OFF to restore the normal new-user behaviour: tips will fire again on their triggers — except anything you marked 'Don't show me again', which stays hidden forever. A brief confirmation card titled 'Welcome tips re-enabled' confirms the switch.\n\nUsed correctly, the tips drop off after the first week and you only see them again if IDMPro ships a meaningful new feature.");

  // Local AI / Ollama
  const aiOllamaId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiOllamaId, aiId, "Local AI / Ollama", "Run AI features using a local model instead of cloud services.\n\nSetup:\n1. Install Ollama (ollama.ai) on your machine — version 0.20+ required for Gemma 4 support\n2. Pull a model: ollama pull gemma4:e4b (recommended for most users)\n3. In IDMPro: Settings > AI Provider\n4. Choose 'Local (Ollama)' or 'Auto'\n\n**Provider Options:**\n- Cloud: Uses cloud AI (default)\n- Local (Ollama): Uses your local Ollama instance on localhost:11434\n- Auto: Tries local first, falls back to cloud if unavailable\n\n**Recommended Models (Gemma 4 — released April 2026):**\n- gemma4:e2b — Lightweight (~1.5GB RAM), mobile-friendly, multimodal\n- gemma4:e4b — RECOMMENDED (~4GB RAM), multimodal, best balance for most systems\n- gemma4:26b — High quality (~16GB RAM), Mixture of Experts, fast despite size\n- gemma4:31b — Maximum quality (~24GB RAM), beats Llama 4 on benchmarks\n\n**Legacy fallback:**\n- llama3.2 — For systems with less than 4GB RAM\n\nIDMPro automatically selects the best model installed based on your system memory. Gemma 4 models support text + image (multimodal), enabling local image analysis without sending to cloud.\n\nLocal AI keeps your data on your machine and works offline.\n\n**Automatic fallback (AI resilience):** The Help chat honors your AI Provider setting. On 'Cloud' or 'Auto', if the cloud AI is unavailable — an outage, a rate limit, or a billing/quota problem — and you have a local Gemma model installed, the Help chat automatically answers with local Gemma instead and shows a calm notice ('Gemini is unavailable right now — answered with local Gemma instead. Quality may differ.'). If the failing key is your OWN key (BYOK) and it's a billing/quota problem, the notice also reminds you to check your provider's billing. If no local model is installed, you'll see a brief 'AI is temporarily unavailable — please try again shortly.' On 'Local', the Help chat always answers with local Gemma and never calls the cloud.");

  // AI Data Consent
  const aiConsentId = uuidv4();
  createNode(nodes, aiConsentId, aiId, "AI Data Consent & Privacy", "IDMPro requires your explicit consent before sending data to AI services.\n\n**First-time consent:**\nWhen you use any AI feature for the first time, a consent dialog appears explaining which services process your data:\n- **Google Gemini** — text generation, content expansion, outline creation\n- **OpenAI** — podcast audio synthesis (text-to-speech)\n- **AssemblyAI** — audio transcription\n\nYou must click 'I Agree' to enable AI features. If you decline, all non-AI features remain fully functional.\n\n**Managing consent:**\nGo to Settings > Data & Privacy to toggle AI data processing on or off at any time.\n\n**Privacy Policy:**\nAvailable at /privacy. Your outlines are stored locally on your device and are never uploaded for storage. Data is only sent to AI services when you explicitly invoke an AI feature.");

  // Safety & Control
  createNode(nodes, aiSafetyId, aiId, "Safety & Control", "You're always in control:\n\n- All AI content is fully editable - change or delete anything\n- Preview mode shows changes before they're applied\n- No automatic modifications to your content\n- Auto-save preserves all changes (including AI content)\n- Undo by using browser back or editing content\n\nAI is a tool to help you - the final decisions are always yours.");

  // Knowledge Chat
